reviewText:
After the hype, the wonder and the excitement wear off, you're left alone in the cold deep space to think about why did you bought this game.

Likes:
- Beautiful and well done visuals and art direction;
- Great VR integration;
- Interesting and innovative gameplay (for a while, at least);
- Rewarding combat.

Dislikes:
- P2P structure instead of server based;
- Stutters and little 'hidden loading' fps drops, even after a major overhaul of hardware;
- Repetitive gameplay;
- Lack of story driven content;
- Lack of entry level guidance;
- Bland, repetitive locations;
- Lackluster features and lack of promised features;
- Multiplayer and instancing issues;
- Unbalanced 'crime' system;
- Unbalanced professions;
- General shallowness of content.

I really wanted to like this game. For a little while, I did. And in some ways, I still do. But after nearly 300 hours, a lot of agravattion in the forums and looking around for developer diaries and interviews, I came to the conclusion that this game can  be better described as a disappointment. But why does a game that offered me such long playtime cannot be recommended?

The main positive point here is the visuals. When you first enter the 'bulk', the subtle humming noise of your ship's engine, the frantic and chaotic combat, the amazingly well done stations and ships... You simply get overwhelmed. Everything is done with attention to detail and quality. But, as it is with most visuals, only the most gullible players remain entertained with sparkle and fizzles after a while.

The bulk, something you find amazing at first, eventually becomes more an annoyance then anything. The constant FTL jumps fruit of a compartmentalized game world severely break the immersion, detracting from the game. The sound and music, so repetitive and limited, eventually fade and, often, you'll see yourself listening to something else on headphones. The stations, amazingly well done as they are, are not unique in any way, being one a copy of the other with minor differences.

And after this fades away, the grinding of the gameplay shows itself and the games loses all momentum and, much like the Gamespot review puts it, the billion star wide game shows that it's one inch deep. Just to give some perspective, from my total play time, over 170~180 hours consisted of my grinding trade routes. I watched series and films in a second monitor and simply paid minor attention to the game - it became a chore. The combat, that is so rewarding on itself, does nothing for the immersion, because after hundreds of faceless, expressionless enemies downed, every ship you blast away is nothing more than a little more credits in the grind.

But in all honesty, I could live with all this and still recommend the game. What makes me warn you to stay away are the two features introduced earlier this year: Powerplay and CQC. Both are unbalanced and unwanted features that were not promised during early backing that simply try to add depth to the MP aspect of the game - and fail. Basic MP features, like player guilds and global chat are nowhere in the game, things that could considerably improve the game's focus on a MP experience, but they choose instead gimmicky, 'new' features, to entice players into buying the game - instead of pleasing the community. CQC in particular is something that I've seen very little vocal support, if we can consider 'uh, I don't know, maybe I don't care if they add it' as 'support'. Powerplay is laughable: instead of improving and expanding on minor factions - which were a source of real fun for players, who could help shape the galaxy in really interesting and seamless ways - they added 'middle' factions, that are utterly and totally unnecessary.

And these days, I log into the game once in a while, and gaze, sadly, the stars of what could have been the best game of all time, knowing that the moment a better experience appears on the gaming horizon, this game is going to never be played again by me.

After playing this game thirty hours, fifteen of which was figuring out the mechanics and map and controls, five of which was researching via third party websites and such what exactly is going on (where to buy different ships, what the different parts really mine, different types of cargo and your effect, etc etc) and ten hours actually sitting down and playing my thought is this;

It's just not worth the effort. Fundamnetally you're playing an mmo wherein the spaceship is your character and there's too much filler and not enough oopmh / reward. To me, a game shouldn't be 90% empty space, 10% trying to dock and 10% navigating an interface menu at a station"

Dissapointing ultimately."
